================================================================================
IFCONFIG / IP ADDR:
	Current archlinux relies on 'ip' tool instead of 'ifconfig' for finding out your LAN IP Address.
Other linux distros might use 'ifconfig'. 'curl' is available for fetching the WAN IP Address used,
which is your internet IP Address. 'nmap' is also available to test if a given port is available for connection.


	SOME NETWORK TOOLS
		GETTING YOUR WAN IP ADDRESS USING 'CURL' TOOL
			Your WAN IP Address represents your PC in the Internet.
		This is how computers outside your Local Area Network(LAN) see you on the internet.

		To use any of these methods, you must be connected to the internet.
		If any of these fail, then your computer has not been set with a WAN IP Address:

				$ curl icanhazip.com
					or
				$ curl api.ipify.org
					or
				$ curl ipinfo.io/ip
					or
				$ curl ifconfig.me

		GETTING YOUR LAN IP ADDRESS AND GATEWAY USING 'IP' TOOL
			Note: When your Network Device directly access the internet without
			the use a router, then this method will get you access to your WAN IP Adress instead.

			The LAN IP Address represents your PC in the local area network.

			1) Fetching local GATEWAY:
				$ ip route show
					or
				$ ip route show | grep -i default | awk '{ print $3}'

			2) Fetching local IP:
				$ ip addr
					or
				$ ip addr show eth0 | grep -oP '(?<= inet\s)\d+(\.\d+){3}'

		
		TESTING PORT AVAILABILITY FOR CONNECTION
			'nmap' will scan for open, closed and filtered ports.

			1) Scanning for Open Ports on a given IP Address:
				$ nmap -p- -Pn <ip_address>

			2) Scanning a single port from a given IP Address:
				$ nmap -p 21 -Pn <ip_address> 


	ALTERNATIVE OPTION(archlinux):
		you can use 'archey4' to see your IP Address.

PARTX -s /dev/sdc:
PARTX -L:
You can use partx -l command to list the partitions in order to find the used space and can subtract from total space. You shall notice that but all numbers are in 512-byte sectors.
