--- SOME GOOGLE STUFF
	
	GOOGLE PROMPTS
		Whenever using a physical android or virtual android,
		Google automatically activates 'google prompts'.

		After 'Google Prompt' is active, the android cellphone/smartphone/mobile device can receive
		prompts asking to permit/allow authorization for other devices, enhancing security whenever a google
		is used on another android cellphone/smartphone/mobile device.

		DISABLING GOOGLE PROMPTS
				The google prompt is used to recognize a new device using your google account as 
			being actually yours, but this notice will only be sent to the main recognized device(s). 

			However, there's always the possibility you can lose access to the device either by theft,
			broken device or if the data gets corrupted rendering you without access to your google account
			on any other device and this can be a problem.

			As of current date, it's not possible to permanently disable 'google prompt'.
			However, you can force it off on a single device by accessing your google account and
			selectively choose the device you want 'google prompt' to be 'off', then finally tell google to 
			log it off. Another solution is to log off all devices.

				
				DISABLING GOOGLE PROMPT FOR A SINGLE DEVICE BY LOGGING IT OFF
					1A) Go to your GmaiL Account >> Click on 'Security' >> Click on 'Google Prompts' >> 
					Click on 'Manage Devices' >> CHOOSE A DEVICE and click on 'log off'
				
				DISABLING GOOGLE PROMPT FOR ALL DEVICES BY LOGGING OFF ALL DEVICES
					1B) Go to your GmaiL Account >> Click on 'Security' >> Click on 'Google Prompts' >> 
					Click on 'Manage Devices' >> Click on 'Don't recognize something?'.

			To summon it up: 'Google Prompt' is mostly a problem when you want to login into google from
			another mobile device, most likely 'Google Play' won't allow you to login from a different
			device without at least having one of your already prompted devices for confirmation.

	USING AN AUTHENTICATOR | MOZILLA FIREFOX ONLY
		Some web services like Google, Hotmail and Github allow using a one-pass only authenticator,
		On firefox, one can just install the authenticator below:

			https://github.com/Authenticator-Extension/Authenticator

		it can also be used as a 2FA(Two Factor Authenticator), only when allowed on some web services.

	KEEPING ACCOUNT ACCESS SAFE | LINUX ONLY
		It's possible to keep account access permanently safe,
		Some web browsers like mozilla firefox allow backing up session profiles, saving cookies, 
		logins to websites, and user enabled authenticators.

		If you desire to do so, you can just backup your firefox profile using this 'zsh' script:
			[file: ~/mozilla_backup_script.zsh ]
				export USERNAME="YOUR_USERNAME";
				cd /;
				rm ./home/${USERNAME}/mozilla\ profile/;
				dar -c mozilla\ profile -Kscram:PASSWORD -g ./home/${USERNAME}/.mozilla;
				cp -ar ./mozilla\ profile ./home/${USERNAME}/
			[/file]
			NOTE: In this script, make sure to change the password as you'd like.
			NOTE2: Make sure you're still logged in all your web services 
			       before making a backup. 
			NOTE3: As of current date, the cache folder for ~/.cache/mozilla isn't needed and
			       can be discarded, only the profile at ~/.mozilla is needed.
			NOTE5: Make sure to backup this data in other devices.
			NOTE4: You'll need to do all these steps again if you ever change password
			       to any of your web services.

