--- SOME HARDWARE STUFF

	MOTHERBOARD POWER ON PINS | MOTHERBOARD FRONT PANEL CONNECTORS RESERVED PIN
		This is usually a pain to do without the motherboard manual, so I've decided to leave this here.
	This should cover at least some if not most low-end to mid-end motherboards, 
	do not attempt this if your have more or less pins, below are the reference illustration:
			|1122X|		or	|33556|
			|33556|			|1122X|


		NOTE: If your Motherboard Pins look different, do not touch anything without reading your very own manual.
		The pin marked as 'X' should not exist here. '6' is never used neither for me.

	Summary:
		1 - Power Led PINS:
			This power led merely indicates when the PC is on.

			Number '1' Pins usually belong to Power Led, unless your motherboard manual says otherwise;
			two pins are used for Power_ON+ and Power_ON-; Some motherboard manuals call it PLED or PWR_LED. 
			PWR_LED+ is on the 1st pin from left to right
			PWR_LED- is on the 2nd pin counting from left to right.

			These pins are represented by '11' on the reference illustration above.

			VERY IMPORTANT: If the connecting cable has an arrow, connect it so that the arrow 
			is facing the PWR_LED+ pin. The arrow indicates the PWR_LED+ in this case.
			Do not touch anything if you're unsure.

		2 - Power Switch PINS:
			These pins refer to the POWER SWITCH Button for turning your PC on.
			The number '2' pins are actually PWRBTN and GND; without them pressing the POWER ON button will
			not turn your PC on. these are mandatory.

			These pins are represented by '22' on the reference illustration above.

			VERY IMPORTANT: If the connecting cable has an arrow, connect it so that the arrow 
			is facing the PWRBTN pin. The arrow indicates the PWRBTN pin.
			Do not touch anything if you're unsure.

		3 - Reset Switch PINS:
			These pins are represented by '55' pins on the reference illustration.
			Without them you can not reset your PC using the 'reset' button.

			VERY IMPORTANT: If the connecting cable has an arrow, connect it so that the arrow 
			is facing the PWRBTN pin. The arrow indicates the very first pin from left to right.
			Do not touch anything if you're unsure.

		4 - Hard Drive Activity Led PINS:
			Represented by '33' on the reference illustration above.
			This is merely used by the motherboard to let the user know the hard drive is working.

			VERY IMPORTANT: If the connecting cable has an arrow, connect it so that the arrow 
			is facing the PWRBTN pin. The arrow indicates the very first pin from left to right.
			Do not touch anything if you're unsure.

		5 - +5V DC PIN / Reserved Pin:
			Represented by '6' on the reference illustration above.

			On my motherboard, this is a reserved pin and not used for anything.

		6 - Final Pins:
			The 'X' Pins - on some motherboards - do not exist.
			The '6' Pin is used for +5V DC PIN as described above, however some motherboards may just label
			it as "Reserved Pin".
