SETTING UP A VSFTP SERVER

	INTRODUCTION TO VSFTPD
		VSFTPD is a FTP daemon for setting up FTP Server, it can run via a 'super-server' like 'inetd' or 'xinetd'.
		it can also run as a service or in 'standalone' mode, the later requires 'listen=YES' to be passed as option

		Example 1 - Launching vsftpd in 'standalone' mode:
			$ vsftpd -olisten=YES -oftpd_banner=WELCOME\ TO\ SERVER
		
		A Configuration file defaults to /etc/vsftpd.conf and will overwrite(or overload) any options passed as
		argument through the commandline.
		
		Example 2 - Using configuration file - :
			$ vsftpd -olisten=YES /etc/vsftpd.conf -oftpd_banner=WELCOME\ TO\ SERVER
		
		In this case, if the configuration file contains 'listen=NO', the value passed by the first '-o' argument
		in the commandline will not work. 

		If no configuration file is ever passed as argument, then default configuration file in /etc/vsftpd.conf 
		is loaded.

		Example 3 - Running vsftpd as service in the background - 
			# systemctl start vsftpd

		Example 4 - Enabling vsftpd to run at system boot - 
			# systemctl enable vsftpd
	
	TESTING A RUNNING VSFTPD SERVER BY DOING A LOCAL TEST
		1) First things first, fetch the local IP Address where the server is running:
			$ ip addr show <network_device> | grep -oP '(?<= inet\s)\d+(\.\d+){3}'

			Example:
				$ ip addr show eth0 | grep -oP '(?<= inet\s)\d+(\.\d+){3}'

		
		2) Use 'nmap' to test the connection availability on the given port,
		the default port number is 21; port 20 is just used for data-transfers:
			$ nmap -p <port_number> -Pn <ip_address>

			Example:
				$ nmap -p 21 -Pn 192.168.0.5

		3) 'nmap' will retrieve one of the following STATES:
			3.1 - STATE: Closed
				This means port is closed, which means there's no running service listenning for it.

			3.2 - STATE: Filtered
				This means that the port is available, but connection is filtered by a firewall.

			3.3 - STATE: Open
				This means the port is open and ready for connection through a FTP Client.

			A) If you get connection 'close', your server isn't running likely due to misconfiguration,
			READ MORE ON:
				CONFIGURATION OPTIONS FOR VSFTPD

			B) If you get connection 'filtered', you may need to enable the port on your firewall, 
			READ MORE ON TOPICS:
				LINUX FIREWALLING WITH IPTABLES | NFTABLES
				LISTING HYPER-V FIREWALL SETTINGS
					CHANGING HYPER-V FIREWALL SETTINGS

		4) Testing connection and transfer through an actual CLIENT:
			NOTE: Only do this step if you got 'Open' connection on the 'nmap test on step #3

			Install 'filezilla' FTP Client, set it up and finally connect.
			You will need local users to be able to connect, so make sure you have this option enabled:
				local_enable=YES

			READ MORE ON TOPIC:
				ALLOWING LOCAL USERS TO CONNECT TO THE FTP CLIENT


		5) CONFIGURATION FILE REFERENCE:
		[file: /etc/vsftpd.conf]
			# Example config file /etc/vsftpd.conf
			#
			# The default compiled in settings are fairly paranoid. This sample file
			# loosens things up a bit, to make the ftp daemon more usable.
			# Please see vsftpd.conf.5 for all compiled in defaults.
			#
			# READ THIS: This example file is NOT an exhaustive list of vsftpd options.
			# Please read the vsftpd.conf.5 manual page to get a full idea of vsftpd's
			# capabilities.
			#
			# Allow anonymous FTP? (Beware - allowed by default if you comment this out).
			anonymous_enable=NO
			#
			# Uncomment this to allow local users to log in.
			local_enable=YES
			#
			# Uncomment this to enable any form of FTP write command.
			#write_enable=YES
			#
			# Default umask for local users is 077. You may wish to change this to 022,
			# if your users expect that (022 is used by most other ftpd's)
			#local_umask=022
			#
			# Uncomment this to allow the anonymous FTP user to upload files. This only
			# has an effect if the above global write enable is activated. Also, you will
			# obviously need to create a directory writable by the FTP user.
			#anon_upload_enable=YES
			#
			# Uncomment this if you want the anonymous FTP user to be able to create
			# new directories.
			#anon_mkdir_write_enable=YES
			#
			# Activate directory messages - messages given to remote users when they
			# go into a certain directory.
			dirmessage_enable=YES
			#
			# Activate logging of uploads/downloads.
			xferlog_enable=YES
			#
			# Make sure PORT transfer connections originate from port 20 (ftp-data).
			connect_from_port_20=YES
			#
			# If you want, you can arrange for uploaded anonymous files to be owned by
			# a different user. Note! Using "root" for uploaded files is not
			# recommended!
			#chown_uploads=YES
			#chown_username=whoever
			#
			# You may override where the log file goes if you like. The default is shown
			# below.
			#xferlog_file=/var/log/vsftpd.log
			#
			# If you want, you can have your log file in standard ftpd xferlog format.
			# Note that the default log file location is /var/log/xferlog in this case.
			#xferlog_std_format=YES
			#
			# You may change the default value for timing out an idle session.
			#idle_session_timeout=600
			#
			# You may change the default value for timing out a data connection.
			#data_connection_timeout=120
			#
			# It is recommended that you define on your system a unique user which the
			# ftp server can use as a totally isolated and unprivileged user.
			nopriv_user=ftpsecure
			#
			# Enable this and the server will recognise asynchronous ABOR requests. Not
			# recommended for security (the code is non-trivial). Not enabling it,
			# however, may confuse older FTP clients.
			#async_abor_enable=YES
			#
			# By default the server will pretend to allow ASCII mode but in fact ignore
			# the request. Turn on the below options to have the server actually do ASCII
			# mangling on files when in ASCII mode.
			# Beware that on some FTP servers, ASCII support allows a denial of service
			# attack (DoS) via the command "SIZE /big/file" in ASCII mode. vsftpd
			# predicted this attack and has always been safe, reporting the size of the
			# raw file.
			# ASCII mangling is a horrible feature of the protocol.
			#ascii_upload_enable=YES
			#ascii_download_enable=YES
			#
			# You may fully customise the login banner string:
			ftpd_banner=Welcome to FTP service.
			#
			# You may specify a file of disallowed anonymous e-mail addresses. Apparently
			# useful for combatting certain DoS attacks.
			#deny_email_enable=YES
			# (default follows)
			#banned_email_file=/etc/vsftpd.banned_emails
			#
			# You may specify an explicit list of local users to chroot() to their home
			# directory. If chroot_local_user is YES, then this list becomes a list of
			# users to NOT chroot().
			# (Warning! chroot'ing can be very dangerous. If using chroot, make sure that
			# the user does not have write access to the top level directory within the
			# chroot)
			#chroot_local_user=YES
			#chroot_list_enable=YES
			# (default follows)
			#chroot_list_file=/etc/vsftpd.chroot_list
			#
			# You may activate the "-R" option to the builtin ls. This is disabled by
			# default to avoid remote users being able to cause excessive I/O on large
			# sites. However, some broken FTP clients such as "ncftp" and "mirror" assume
			# the presence of the "-R" option, so there is a strong case for enabling it.
			#ls_recurse_enable=YES
			#
			# When "listen" directive is enabled, vsftpd runs in standalone mode and
			# listens on IPv4 sockets. This directive cannot be used in conjunction
			# with the listen_ipv6 directive.
			listen=YES
			#
			# This directive enables listening on IPv6 sockets. To listen on IPv4 and IPv6
			# sockets, you must run two copies of vsftpd with two configuration files.
			# Make sure, that one of the listen options is commented !!
			#listen_ipv6=YES

			# Set own PAM service name to detect authentication settings specified
			# for vsftpd by the system package.
			pam_service_name=vsftpd

			## Custom Settings
			max_clients=1

			## This is a list of users not allowed to login:
			userlist_enable=YES
			userlist_file=/etc/vsftpd.userlist
			#userlist_deny=NO -- this doesn't works

			## This is required for WSL2
			seccomp_sandbox=NO
			isolate_network=NO

			## Enables TLS for data encryption during transfers
			#ssl_enable=YES
		[/file]

	FTP USER PERMISSIONS
		VSFTPD uses PAM for user authentication, this means all local users and respective passwords 
		are available as login for the VSFTPD server.
		
		FTP File and data permissions used are the same ones used on the filesystem.

		In case you need to harden the permissions, READ MORE ON:
			THE VERY BASICS ABOUT FILESYSTEM USER AND GROUP OWNERSHIP

	CONFIGURATION OPTIONS FOR VSFTPD
		Configurations can be set on /etc/vsftpd.conf by either commenting or uncommenting and
		by giving them a value.

		SETTING UP NO-PRIVILEGED USER FOR THE SERVER TO RUN AS
			This allows the server to run as an unprivileged user called 'ftpsecure',
			so make sure to create the user by hand.

			1) Create user as root:
				# useradd --shell /usr/bin/zsh --create-home ftpsecure

			2) Change password for the given user:
				# passwd ftpsecure

			Example:
				nopriv_user=ftpsecure

		SETTING UP MAXIMUM NUMBER OF CONNECTED CLIENTS
			For increased security, you can setup maximum number of connected clients to '1',
			this way only one user is allowed to connect at all times.

			Example:
				max_clients=1
		
		ALLOWING LOCAL USERS TO CONNECT TO THE FTP CLIENT
			This will allow local users to connect to the FTP Client,
			can be used for testing, and can be later disabled for extra security.

			Example:
				local_enable=YES

		DISABLING ANONYMOUS CONNECTIONS
			Disable "guest" users from connecting to the FTP Server.
			by default, vsftpd uses local login passwords as FTP Accounts.

			Example:
				anonymous_enable=NO
		
		DISABLING LOCAL ACCOUNTS FROM VSFTP ACCESS
			It's possible to disable local accounts from being accessed remotely from a client connection
			to the server by creating a 'userlist' configuration file and enabling these options:

			Example:
				userlist_enable=YES
				userlist_file=/etc/vsftpd.userlist

		ENABLING VSFTP PORT TO BE FOUND FROM A CONTAINER 
			This is a necessary step if you want the VSFTPD server to be found from container-like
			environments like WSL or Firejail.

			Example:
				seccomp_sandbox=NO
				isolate_network=NO

	SETTING UP VSFTPD SERVER FROM A WSL DISTRO | SETTING UP A SERVER IN WSL
		For a quick configuration, you'll have to ADD these settings to your .wslconfig file:

		[file: /mnt/c/Users/<username>/.wslconfig
			##Defaults to 'false' - allows windows firewalling on WSL
			##- ENABLE THIS FOR SERVERS:
			firewall=true

			##Defaults to 'false' - Changes how DNS requests are proxied from WSL to Windows.
			##- ENABLE THIS FOR SERVERS
			dnsTunneling=true

			##Defaults to 'false' - Enforces WSL to use Windows HTTP proxy information.
			##- ENABLE THIS FOR SERVERS
			autoProxy=true

			##If the value is mirrored then this turns on mirrored networking mode.
			##Default or unrecognized strings result in NAT networking. Default value is NAT.
			##- ENABLE THIS FOR SERVERS
			networkingMode=mirrored
		[/file]

		
		1 - SETTING UP WINDOWS FIREWALL TO MAKE WSL DISTRO VISIBLE IN LAN
			It's important to understand how microsoft firewall works at this point,
		Microsoft Windows Firewall has 3 profiles:
			A) Domain
				This is the ideal profile if you're in a LAN that's under the administration
			of a Domain Controller.

			B) Private
				This is a more loose security firewall profile, it assumes
			you're using your PC from your Home Network and assumes devices in the LAN
			can be trusted.

			C) Public
				The most secure firewall profile, will by defaul prevent your PC
			from being found in the LAN and WAN and prevent most INBOUND connections
			from happening.

		All 3 firewall profiles can be active at the same time.
		Although exceptions can be made by port-forwarding and NAT Rules, some pre-built default firewal
		settings can not be overriden nor changed by the user nor the administration.

		Because of this, if you want your Web/FTP/SSH Server to be visible in LAN you'll have
		to consider these three points:

			1) Disable the Public Profile on the Microsoft Windows Firewall and/or
			use a 3rd party firewall for windows.

			2) Besides Disabling the 'Public Profile', you also have to 
			change your Network Device to the 'Private Profile'. The Network Device Profile works
			similarly to how the firewall profiles does, except that there's no 'Domain' profile
			for it.

			3) Create NAT Rules nd Port-Fowarding rules in your Router if you want external network 
			visibility. Only servers deployed in virtual sub-networks will require this step or
			if one requires exposure of the server to the WAN.

		1.2 - NOTE ON PORT-FORWARDING ON MICROSOFT WINDOWS FIREWALL
			Port-Forwarding with 'Public Profile' turned on doesn't work.
		As stated before, microsoft firewall has pre-built rules that can not be 
		overriden/overloaded/overwritten/changed. 'Public Profile' has to be disabled and Network Device
		also has to use 'Private Profile'.

		IMPORTANT NOTE: Use a 3rd party commercial firewall if you dislike the lack of flexibility.
		However, the use of a 3rd party firewall will disable microsoft windows firewalling and may add
		further and more complex configuration options.

		1.3 - (OPTIONAL) - CREATING A NAT RULE FOR A WSL SERVER
			Setting up a NAT Rule is only a required step if you want 
		server exposure to devices connected from an external networks.

			To access your router configurations, use the instructions given by the router and use
		it's admin username/password and setup a new NAT Rule from there.

			Note: Since Routers have different ways of setting up NAT Rules and Port-Forward rules,
		i'll not be covering this step-by-step.

		1.4 - (OPTIONAL) - PORT-FORWARDING FOR A WSL SERVER
			Port-forwarding is only required if you run into issues; it will likely not be a problem
		when devices are connected to same LAN as the server.
		
		1.5 - DISABLING PUBLIC PROFILE FOR NETWORK DEVICE ADAPTER
			From windows 11, press 'system_key + i', then go for 'Network and Internet',
		finally choose your Network Device and then set your Network Profile to 'Private' for less
		restrictive networking rules and visibility to other devices.

		1.6 - DISABLING PUBLIC PROFILE FROM WINDOWS FIREWALL
			From windows 11, press 'system_key + i', then go for 'Network and Internet',
		click on 'Windows Firewall' option and wait for Windows Defender to launch.

			Once Windows Defender is launched, click 'Firewall and Network Protection',
		then finally disable 'Public Profile'.
			
		1.7 - (Optional) - DISABLING PUBLIC PROFILE ONLY FOR SPECIFIC NETWORK DEVICE
			Windows allows disabling a Profile for the Virtual WSL Network Device.
		You can use this and test as an alternate route to the above #5.1.5 step.

			To do this, From windows 11, press 'system_key + r', type 'wf.msc' or 'WF.msc',
		Right-Click on the option 'Windows Firewall Defender' located right above 'Inbound rules',
		Click on 'Properties', then for 'Public profile' click on  'Protected Network Connections',
		finally uncheck the Network Device for disabling the profile.

		1.8 - ENABLING WINDOWS FIREWALL LOGS FOR SAFETY
			From windows 11, press 'system_key + r', type 'wf.msc' or 'WF.msc',
		Right-Click on the option 'Windows Firewall Defender' located right above 'Inbound rules',
		Click on 'Properties' and then Enable Log for each active profiles: 'Domain', 'Public' 'Private'.

			You can easily read the logs by clicking on 'Monitoring'; if you can't see this option,
		then double-click on the 'Windows Firewall Defender' for expanding and making more options visible.

			Note: you want this enabled if you're running any server.

		1.9 - (OPTIONAL) - CREATING NEW INBOUND AND OUTBOUND FIREWALL RULES ON WINDOWS
			Inbound and Outbound rules can be created from 'wf.msc' tool.

		1.10 - (OPTIONAL) - WSL HYPER-V FIREWALL SETTINGS
			Read more on:
				LISTING HYPER-V FIREWALL SETTINGS

