---------------
FILESYSTEM ENCRYPTION USING GOCRYPTFS
	REQUIREMENTS FOR USING GOCRYPTFS
		GOCRYPTFS requires a 'Fuse' enabled kernel and also 'fuse' to be installed on the linux system.
		Here's a small list of packages required on archlinux:

			1 - fuse2
				Older fuse version, allows for backwards compatibility.

			2 - fuse3
				Newer version of fuse.

			3 - psmisc
				Allows 'fuser' to be used for killing/shutting down processes that have kept
				a hold on files/data even tho they have been closed. On archlinux, 'psmisc' is installed
				alongside the 'base' package.

	ADVANTAGES OF GOCRYPTFS OVER ENCFS

		A) 'Encfs' isn't maintained nor supported anylonger.
		B) 'Gocryptfs' is 'encfs' spiritual successor.
		C) Just like 'encfs' it can be used on any filesystem, including remote storages filesystems.
		D) unlike 'encfs', 'gocryptfs' allows specifying configuration key file from the moment it's created.
		E) unlike 'encfs', 'gocryptfs' has multi-threading support.

	INITIALIZING A GOCRYPTFS ENCRYPTED DIRECTORY
		1) First create a directory meant for storage:
			$ mkdir ~/Encrypted.storage

			1A) Note: When creating directories on a remote storage, make sure that DIRECTORY CREATION
			and INITIALIZATION is done directly in the remote storage.

		2) Initialize the encrypting directory: 
			$ gocrypfs --config "/etc/gocryptfs/gdrive_cougar_A.conf" --init ~/Encryted.storage
				or
			$ gocrypfs --config --deterministic-names "/etc/gocryptfs/gdrive_cougar_A.conf" --init ~/Encryted.storage

			2A) Note: when not specifying '--config', a .conf file will be created at the encrypted.storage
			directory.

			2B) Note: An extra .diriv file will be created at encrypted.storage directory,
			this file can not be stored elsewhere and it's related to hiding directory name and file names by
			obfuscating them behind completely random names.

			2C) Note: Cloud storage might have issues with files that are accessed/read too many times
			as is the case with .diriv file, make sure to enable cached mode '--vfs-cache-mode full' 
			when using a tool like 'rclone'. If this is a problem for you, .diriv file can be disabled 
			with the --deterministic-names option upon creation and mount.
			
			2D) Note: Backup both .conf and .diriv, the .diriv file needs to be backed up from time to 
			time as new files are added or renamed.
		
	MOUNTING GOCRYPTFS ENCRYPTED DIRECTORY
		$ gocryptfs --config "/etc/gocryptfs/gdrive_cougar_A.conf" ~/Encrypted.storage ~/Mount.point
			or
		$ gocryptfs --deterministic-names --config "/etc/gocryptfs/gdrive_cougar_A.conf" ~/Encrypted.storage ~/Mount.point

		A) Note: Only specify --deterministic-names for mounting if you have initialized/created a 'gocryptfs' 
		with it.

	CHANGING GOCRYPTFS PASSWORD TO AN ENCRYPTED DIRECTORY
		$ gocryptfs --passwd ~/Encrypted.storage
			or
		$ gocryptfs --config "/etc/gocryptfs/gdrive_cougar_A.conf" --passwd ~/Encrypted.storage

