---------------
FILESYSTEM ENCRYPTION USING ENCFS
	ENCFS REQUIREMENTS 
		EncFS requires a 'Fuse' enabled kernel and also 'fuse' to be installed on the linux system.
	Here's a small list of packages required on archlinux:

		1 - fuse2
			Older fuse version, allows for backwards compatibility.

		2 - fuse3
			Newer version of fuse.

		3 - psmisc
			Allows 'fuser' to be used for killing/shutting down processes that have kept
			a hold on files/data even tho they have been closed. On archlinux, 'psmisc' is installed
			alongside the 'base' package.
			
	
	ADVANTAGES OF ENCFS
		source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EncFS

		A) EncFS is a fuse based virtual encrypted layer. 
		EncFS doesn't requires specific filesystem features and it doesn't requires the whole
		block-device to be used, allowing directories within already partitioned filesystems to be used
		for encryption, this means EncFS works on top of literally any 
		known filesystem(BTRFS, Ext4, XFS, NFS, etc).

		B) EncFS allows disk size to be shrinked or expanded on-the-fly as data is either added or removed 
		without requiring any commands or extra tools. This refers to scalable storage.

		C) EncFS can be directly used on remote cloud storages, allowing the user to read the stored cloud data
		without ever exposing the decrytped data to the cloud service when used alongside tools like 'rclone'.

		D) EncFS is able to store each unique volume key anywhere else than the actual encrypted data, such as 
		on a USB flash drive, network mount, optical disc or cloud. In addition to that a password could 
		be required to decrypt this volume key. By default, key file is stored on the encrypted directory as
		a hidden file named .encfs6.xml.

		E) EncFS is available on multiple different platforms. Again, it's not tied to the kernel or specific
		filesystem features.

		F) A Faster Backup on cloud storage is possible, since only the modified data will be uploaded.

		G) Reduced Data corruption, since filesystem utilities like 'fsck'(for EXT4 filesystems only) can be 
		normally utilized to fix filesystem problems and fix data encrypted with EncFS. EncFS also offers bitrot
		detection.

		H) Files can be accessed at random. You can, for example, skip to the middle of a very large encrypted 
		video without decrypting the whole file.

		I) Features from most modern available File Systems can be fully utilized when accessing
		and reading both the encrypted/decrypted data.

	CREATING AN ENCRYPTED STORAGE AND MOUNT-DECRYPTING IT WITH ENCFS
		1) MODPROBING REQUIRED ENCFS MODULES
			Some linux distros might requiring modprobing first on the fuse module:
				# modprobe fuse

		2) CREATING AN ENCRYPTED ENCFS DIRECTORY
			Note: EncFS only accepts absolute paths, not relative ones; in other words, 
			using characters like '~' or './' is not allowed.

			Setting up EncFS for a given directory is as easy as this:
				$ encfs /path/to/storage /path/to/mount


			2A) Note: /path/to/mount is only used as a pseudo directory for exposing the decrypted data 
			to the user. /path/to/storage is used as actual data storage where the data is encrypted 
			and stored on-the-fly as the user uses the data on /path/to/mount.
			
			2B) It's recommended to use 'Paranoia Mode' if you want strict security.

			2C) Note: Environment variable 'ENCFS6_CONFIG' can NOT be set before setting up a new encrypted
			directory; HOWEVER, it can be set for decrypting an already existing encrypted directory using 
			.encfs6.xml file from a different directory than the default dir., thus this allows the Key File 
			to be safely stored elsewhere.

				Example 1 - Mounting an already encrypted storage on decryption mount-point - :
					$ ENCFS6_CONFIG=/home/me/.encfs6.xml encfs /path/to/storage /path/to/mount


			2.1) SETTING UP CUSTOM LOCAL STORAGE PATH FOR ENCFS KEYS
				As seen in Example 2 above, you can set a different directory for the key file
			and give it a different name. 

				2.1.1) Create the new encfs directory:
					# mkdir /etc/encfs/

				2.1.2) Give yourself access to the directory by setting up read/write/execute modes:
					# setfacl -m u:${USER}:rwx /etc/encfs/

				2.1.3) Simplify the task by setting the path as an environment variables:
				you can later use auto-completion features from zsh/bash:

					[file: /etc/environment]
						GDRIVE_COUGAR="/etc/my_encfs_keys/.google_cougar.xml"
					[/file]

					Note: you can load /etc/environment straight to your current shell session
					using source command as follows:
						$ source /etc/environment

				2.1.4) Create the new encrypted directory on a trusted storage that belongs to you:
					$ encfs /path/to/storage /path/to/mount

					Note: The key file will always be created in the default dir. /path/to/storage.

				2.1.5) Now Copy the Key file to the directory created on step #2.1.1
				Using the filename specified in step #2.1.3.

					Note: Pay attention to Key Filename in order to not replace/overwrite
					any existing keys, or you might permanently lose access to any other
					encrypted data.

					$ mv /path/to/storage/.encfs6.xml /etc/encfs/.google_cougar.xml

				2.1.6)(OPTIONAL) Copy the encrypted directory to a CLOUD STORAGE service.

					2.1.6.1) Umount first before deleting local files:
						$ fusermount -u /path/to/mount

					2.1.6.2) If you have cloud storage set with 'rclone' you may simply copy into it 
					after mounting it with 'rclone':
						$ mv /path/to/storage /path/to/google\ drive/

					2.1.6.3) After copying to google drive, you can safely remove 
					local mount folder created when setting up encfs:
						$ rm -r /path/to/mount

				2.1.7) Now mount the encrypted data now located on the cloud storage and using
				a local key file:
						$ ENCFS6_CONFIG=${GOOGLEDRIVE_COUGAR} encfs /path/to/storage /path/to/mount

		3) MOUNTING ENCRYPTED ENCFS DIRECTORY
			It can be done the same way, encfs will automatically detect when setup has already occurred,
			and simply mount encrypted data on the decryption mount-point:

				$ encfs /path/to/storage /path/to/mount


			3.1)(ALTERNATE OPTION - OPTIONAL) Using custom path for encfs6.xml file:
				Use this for decrypting data if you have followed step #2C above:			
					$ ENCFS6_CONFIG=/home/me/.encfs6.xml encfs /tmp/crypt-view /tmp/plain-view

		5) CONFIRMING ENCFS DECRYPTED DATA HAS BEEN PROPERLY MOUNTED
			You can make sure encfs has been mounted correctly,
		this will show you how much disk space you have available, it should be the same as the 
		cloud storage device or the hard disk you've decided to use.
				$ df -h 

		4) BACKING UP ENCFS KEY FILE
			By default, EncFS stores the key file on the encrypted directory /path/to/storage as
			a hidden file named .encfs6.xml, without this file it'll not be possible to decrypt the
			encrypted data anylonger.

			If your data is too important, you always have the option to store this file elsewhere
			and remove it from the default encrypted directory.

			One way or another, always backup this file.


	UMOUNTING ENCFS DIRECTORY
		This is how to umount a fuse based device:
			$ fusermount -u /path/to/mount/

		Or Umounting by fuse device name:
			$ fusermount -u <Name of the FUSE Device>

			ex:
				$ fusermount -u "Proton Drive"
			 	Note: You can use auto-complete feature from bash-zsh by pressing <tab-key>

		Or Lazy Umounting for a forced umount:
			$ fusermount -uz /path/to/mount
				or
			$ fusermount -uz "Proton Drive"

		KILLING ALL PROCESSES USING OR HOLDING DIRECTORY DATA
			Killing processes that are holding on files might be necessary if umounting fails:
				$ fuser --kill ~/path/to/mount/{*,.*}

	CHANGING ENCFS PASSWORD
		$ encfsctl passwd /path/to/storage
			or
		$ ENCFS6_CONFIG="/etc/encfs/.gdrive_cougar.conf"  /path/to/storage

