RCLONE TUTORIAL
	ADDING A NEW REMOTE CLOUD DEVICE
		$ rclone config

	MOUNTING WITH RCLONE 
		$ rclone mount --daemon --vfs-cache-mode full Remote_Name: ./Pseudo-Directory


		A) Note: ./Pseudo-Directory must exist, so make sure you create it first.
		B) Note: Remote_Name is the name you used to setup the storage device when
		setting it up with 'rclone config'
		C) Note: '--vfs-cache-mode full' should cover most setups for free cloud storage drives.
		D) Note: '--daemon' will allow rclone to run as a service(in the background) as opposed to running
		it as a foreground process.

	SETTING UP RCLONE FOR MEGA UPLOAD
		Normally use your email as username and input your password when asked.

	SETTING UP RCLONE FOR PCLOUD STORAGE
		source: https://rclone.org/pcloud/

		Leave Client ID and Client Secret empty, Let everything else set to defaut options.
		When asked to for browser access, say 'yes' and authorize yourself via browser.

	SETTING UP RCLONE FOR ONE DRIVE
		source: https://rclone.org/onedrive/

		When asked for CLIENT ID and CLIENT SECRET, do not enter any input, simply skip it.
		Choose 'GLOBAL' when asked for 'national cloud region' for OneDrive.
		Leave everything else to default option.

		Access the generate URL for OAUTH Authentication.
		Let anything else set to defaut options.


	SETTING UP RCLONE FOR GOOGLE DRIVE
		source:
			https://rclone.org/drive/
		
		When asked for CLIENT ID and CLIENT SECRET, do not give it any input, simply skip it.
		Select 'Full access all files, excluding Application Data Folder' when asked.
		Leave everything else to default option.

		Access the generate URL for OAUTH Authentication.
		Let anything else set to defaut options.



	SETTING UP RCLONE FOR PROTON DRIVE
		source: https://rclone.org/protondrive/#configurations

		Give your email as username and then input your password. Confirm default settings for everything else.
		When asked for 'Advanced Configuration', say 'yes' then input your MAILBOX PASSWORD when asked for it,
		leave everything else to default options.

		NOTE: The Proton Drive encryption keys need to have been already generated after a regular login 
		via the browser, otherwise attempting to use the credentials in rclone will fail.

		Proton Drive support is considered to be in beta test, so might not work with all accounts.

	UMOUNTING RCLONE STORAGE DEVICE
		This is how to umount a fuse based device:
			$ fusermount -u /path/to/mount/

		Or Umounting by fuse device name:
			$ fusermount -u <Name of the FUSE Device>

			ex:
				$ fusermount -u "Proton Drive"
			 	Note: You can use auto-complete feature from bash-zsh by pressing <tab-key>

		Or Lazy Umounting for a forced umount:
			$ fusermount -uz /path/to/mount
				or
			$ fusermount -uz "Proton Drive"

		KILLING ALL PROCESSES USING OR HOLDING DIRECTORY DATA
			Killing processes that are holding on files might be necessary if umounting fails:
				$ fuser --kill ~/path/to/mount/{*,.*}
